vant-garde—one that contests the heteromasculinity and ocular surveillance visited upon it by the larger Chicanx community, as well as the formally straight conditions of traditional archive-building, museum institutions, and the art world writ large. With a focus on works by Mundo Meza (1955–85), Teddy Sandoval (1949–1995), and Joey Terrill (1955– ), and with appearances by Laura Aguilar, David Hockney, Robert Mapplethorpe, and even Eddie Murphy, Archiving an Epidemic composes a complex picture of queer Chicanx avant-gardisms. With over sixty images—many of which are published here for the first time—Hernández’s work excavates this archive to question not what Chicanx art is, but what it could have been.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGay menxSexual behavior. 0aMexican American gays. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aAIDS quilt.  aAby Warburg.  aAlex Donis.  aAlma Lopez.  aAndré Malraux.  aArnie Araica.  aAsco.  aBarrio Baroque.  aBeverly Center.  aCathedral High School.  aCharles Lummis.  aChicano art movement.  aChristopher Isherwood.  aCyclona.  aDavid Hockney.  aDon Bachardy.  aEd Kienholz.  aEddie Murphy.  aErnest Batchelder.  aFire Island.  aFrozen Art.  aGilbert Magú Lujan.  aHomeboy Beautiful.  aJack Vargas.  aJef Huereque.  aJeff Bridges.  aLatino AIDS memorial.  aLos Angeles.  aLuis Jimenez.  aMacho Mirage.  aMaricón Collective.  aMichael Nava.  aModern Objects.  aMundos Alternos.  aNew Romantics.  aPalm Springs.  aPicasso.  aQueer Aztlán.  aRobert Mapplethorpe.  aRonnie Carrillo.  aRon’s Records.  aRosa de la Montaña.  aSelf-Help Graphics.  aSimon Doonan.  aSouthwest Museum.  aarchival body.  aarchival space.  aarchive elicitation.  acast culture.  adomesticana sensibility.  aiconoclasm.  ainstit